Excess leads to waste.  Major retailers have overstock/returns that would end up in landfills. We work with liquidators to bring things to our market that would otherwise go to waste.  
Never underestimate the power of proximity.  Geography affects weather.  Weather impacts consumer needs.  This all feeds into seasonal market demand.  So, what does this have to do with our business model?
Consumers want accurate descriptions and fast shipping.  By sourcing things at a lower cost, we are able to bring them to our market and apply a variable pricing model.  Each product is assigned a minimum floor price.  Using various platforms, consumers can put in their bids for products.  If it is above the floor, they granted the bid and get the product at a price they feel good about.  Prices for like items vary, but none below the floor set.
Having a variable pricing model serves 2 functions: 1) broadens consumer base by its flexible design and 2) gives market research on pricing.

In American law, a signing agent or courtesy signer is an agent whose function is to obtain a formal signature of an appearer to a document. In common parlance, most jurisdictions require the appearer to sign before a notary public. From this, the practice of a notary public designating themselves as a signing agent has arisen. There are notaries public who specialize in the notarization of real estate transfer and loan document signings. Signing agents often have certification and training through private organizations, but is not a requirement in law, although it may be a requirement of the lender in the oversight of real estate transaction document signatures.

Also referred to as a notary signing agent or a loan signing agent, a signing agent should not be confused with a mortgage loan closer or closing agent. Signing agents are notaries public, who usually have experience and/or training concerning the proper execution of loan documents and are hired by mortgage companies, escrow
